    <section id="overview">
      <h2>Year Overview</h2>
      <p>The Rabbit (<span class="chinese-char">兔</span>) occupies the Earthly Branch <strong>Mao (卯)</strong>, carrying Yin Wood energy. In 2026, the Rabbit's relationship with the Fire Horse follows the <strong>generating cycle</strong> — Wood feeds Fire. This creates a year of creative output and social visibility, but unlike the Tiger's powerful Yang Wood connection, the Rabbit's gentler Yin Wood is more susceptible to depletion.</p>
      <p>The Rabbit-Horse relationship carries a <strong>Mao-Wu destruction</strong> (卯午破), a subtle but persistent friction. This isn't as dramatic as a full clash but creates a background tension — things that should go smoothly encounter unexpected snags. Patience and flexibility, the Rabbit's natural strengths, are the best responses.</p>
      <p>The year favours the Rabbit's artistic and diplomatic talents. Fire illuminates Yin Wood's beauty — think of firelight playing across carved wood or candlelight in a garden. The Rabbit's aesthetic sense is appreciated and rewarded, making this an excellent year for creative professionals, designers, writers, and educators.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="career">
      <h2>Career &amp; Finance</h2>
      <p>The Rabbit's career benefits from <strong>increased visibility and creative recognition</strong>. Projects that showcase aesthetic judgment, diplomatic skill, or educational expertise receive positive attention. Collaborative work is favoured over solo ventures — the Rabbit thrives as the creative voice within a supportive team.</p>
      <p><strong>Finance</strong> requires careful management. The generating cycle means money flows outward — generosity, social obligations, and lifestyle upgrades consume income. The Rabbit should establish a savings discipline early in the year before Fire's expansive energy takes hold. Avoid lending money during the summer months.</p>
      <p><strong>Best sectors:</strong> Arts, design, fashion, education, counselling, diplomacy, hospitality, and any field valuing refinement and interpersonal skill.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="love">
      <h2>Love &amp; Relationships</h2>
      <p>Fire's warmth adds <strong>passion and expressiveness</strong> to the Rabbit's normally reserved romantic nature. Existing relationships benefit from the Rabbit's increased willingness to show affection and plan romantic experiences. Partners find the Rabbit more engaging and present.</p>
      <p><strong>Single Rabbits</strong> attract attention through charm and cultural sophistication. The Mao-Wu destruction energy means initial connections may face tests — first impressions need follow-through. The Rabbit's secret friend, the Dog, is an especially compatible match in 2026 (Dog also forms a fire triangle with the year).</p>
      <p><strong>Friendships</strong> are a highlight. The Rabbit's social circle expands, and meaningful connections form through cultural events, creative communities, and educational settings.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="health">
      <h2>Health &amp; Wellness</h2>
      <p>Yin Wood's vulnerability to Fire means the Rabbit must guard against <strong>nervous exhaustion and liver strain</strong>. Overwork, excessive social commitments, and irregular sleep patterns are the primary risks. The Rabbit's tendency to accommodate others' needs before their own is amplified.</p>
      <p><strong>Eye health and tendons</strong> (both governed by Wood/Liver in Chinese medicine) need attention. Screen fatigue is a particular risk. Ensure adequate sleep and include foods that nourish the liver — leafy greens, goji berries, and light soups.</p>
      <p><strong>Gentle exercise</strong> suits the Rabbit's nature: tai chi, qigong, yoga, walking in nature. Avoid extreme or competitive sports that further deplete Yin Wood energy. Meditation and journaling help process the year's heightened emotional activity.</p>
    </section>

